onally adopted for <i>Ó Gibealláin</i>, see   Giblin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gibb","meanings":["English: from the personal name <i>Gibb</i>, a pet form of <i>Gilbert</i> (compare   Gibbs  ). This surname is also frequent in Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":33,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Gibson was born in 1349, in Yorkshire, England, her father, Lord John Gibson, was 49 and her mother, Lora De La Hay De Cummingesburgh, was 49. She married Thomas Metcalf in 1358, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1389, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1349–1389":"1349–1389","1336–1408":"1336–1408","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1358–1467":"1358–1467","130